==English==

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|enm|abundauntly}}, {{m|enm|habundauntly}}, from {{der|en|enm|abundaunt}}, {{m|enm|habundaunt}} + {{m|enm|-ly||in a specified manner}}.<ref name=WI3>{{R:MW3 1976|page=8}}</ref> Equivalent to {{suffix|abundant|ly|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əˈbʌn.dn̩t.li/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/əˈbʌn.dn̩t.li/|/əˈbn̩.dn̩t.li/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-abundantly.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Adverb===
{{en-adv}}

# In an [[abundant]] manner; in a [[sufficient]] degree; fully; [[amply]]; [[plentifully]]; in large [[measure]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=10}}</ref>
#* {{RQ:AV}} Genesis, I, 20
#*: And God said, Let the waters bring forth '''abundantly''' the moving creature that hath life, and fowl that may fly above the earth in the open firmament of heaven.
#* '''1905''', James Geikie, ''Structural and Field Geology: For Students of Pure and Applied Science''
#*: When strata are so unsymmetrically and '''abundantly''' folded that it becomes difficult or impossible to trace out the individual flexures and crumplings — the whole forming an irregular complex of folds — they are said to be contorted {{...}}
#* {{quote-journal|date=May 26, 2012|author=Phil McNulty|title=Norway 0-1 England|work=BBC Sport|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18184726|page=|passage=Hodgson also has Wayne Rooney to call on once he has served a two-match suspension at the start of the tournament - and it is '''abundantly''' clear England will rely as heavily as ever on his ability to shape the outcome of important games.}}
# [[extremely|Extremely]]. {{rfex|lang=en}}

